          "pause": true,
          "displayType": "poster",
          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>Which bone of the neurocranium forms the central skull base and contains a saddl</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>Which bone of the neurocranium forms the central skull base and contains a saddle-shaped depression called the sella turcica?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Ethmoid</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The ethmoid contributes the cribriform plate (for olfactory nerves) and the perpendicular plate for the upper nasal septum. It does not form the central skull base.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Occipital</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The occipital bone closes the skull posteriorly and contains the foramen magnum. The sella turcica is located in the body of the sphenoid, not the occipital bone.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Sphenoid</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. The sphenoid bone forms the central skull base. Its body contains the sella turcica, a saddle-shaped recess that houses the pituitary gland. It also has greater and lesser wings and pterygoid processes.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Temporal</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The temporal bone bears the external acoustic meatus and the mastoid process. The sella turcica is a feature of the sphenoid bone.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "The sella turcica is located in the body of the sphenoid bone. Remember: sphenoid = central skull base, with greater and lesser wings, pterygoid processes, and the sella turcica for the pituitary gland."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Well done! The sphenoid is often called the keystone of the cranium — it articulates with every other cranial bone and houses the pituitary gland in its sella turcica."
                }
              ],
              "behaviour": {
                "enableRetry": true,
