          },
          "pause": true,
          "displayType": "poster",
          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>A patient with a petrous temporal bone fracture presents with facial paralysis a</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>A patient with a petrous temporal bone fracture presents with facial paralysis and hearing loss on the same side. Through which structure in the posterior cranial fossa do the affected nerves pass?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Jugular foramen</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The jugular foramen transmits cranial nerves IX, X, and XI along with the internal jugular vein. A lesion here causes Vernet's syndrome — not facial paralysis or hearing loss.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Foramen magnum</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The foramen magnum transmits the medulla oblongata, vertebral arteries, and the spinal accessory nerve roots. It does not carry the facial or vestibulocochlear nerves.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Internal acoustic meatus</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. Cranial nerves VII (facial) and VIII (vestibulocochlear) pass through the internal acoustic meatus in the petrous part of the temporal bone. A fracture here classically causes ipsilateral facial palsy and sensorineural hearing loss.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Hypoglossal canal</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The hypoglossal canal carries cranial nerve XII, which supplies the tongue muscles. It is not related to hearing or facial movement.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "CN VII (facial) and CN VIII (vestibulocochlear) pass through the internal acoustic meatus. A petrous fracture damages both, causing facial paralysis and hearing loss. Remember: jugular foramen = CN IX, X, XI (Vernet's syndrome); hypoglossal canal = CN XII."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Correct! The internal acoustic meatus carries CN VII and VIII through the petrous temporal bone. This anatomical relationship explains why petrous fractures present with both facial palsy and hearing loss."
                }
              ],
              "behaviour": {
