          "pause": true,
          "displayType": "poster",
          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>Which of the following is a distinguishing feature of the atlas (C1) vertebra?</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>Which of the following is a distinguishing feature of the atlas (C1) vertebra?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>It carries the dens (odontoid process)</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The dens is a feature of the axis (C2), not the atlas. It projects upward from the body of C2 and is held in place by the transverse ligament.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>It has no body and no spinous process</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. The atlas is a ring-shaped bone with two lateral masses, an anterior arch, and a posterior arch. It has neither a vertebral body nor a true spinous process — unique among all vertebrae.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>It has a long, non-bifid spinous process</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>A long, non-bifid spinous process is the hallmark of C7, the vertebra prominens. The atlas has no spinous process at all.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>The vertebral artery does not pass through its transverse foramen</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>This describes C7, not the atlas. The vertebral artery passes through the transverse foramina of C1 through C6, bypassing C7.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "The atlas (C1) has no body and no spinous process. Remember the three atypical cervical vertebrae: C1 (ring, no body), C2 (dens/odontoid), C7 (long non-bifid spine, vertebral artery bypasses its foramen)."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Well done! The atlas is essentially a bony ring — its superior facets articulate with the occipital condyles, enabling the nodding (yes) movement of the head."
                }
              ],
              "behaviour": {
